=es |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322042005/https://caracol.com.co/radio/2020/03/12/economia/1584018532_364941.html |archive-date=22 March 2020 |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Mexican peso]] also set an all-time record low against the U.S. dollar, trading at 22.99 pesos.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/cartera/finanzas/dolar-abre-en-rompe-maximo-historico |title=D\u00f3lar alcanza m\u00e1ximo hist\u00f3rico de 22.98 pesos en la madrugada |date=12 March 2020 |access-date=12 March 2020 |language=es |website=El Universal}}</ref> The cryptocurrency [[Bitcoin]] dropped 40%, its worst day in 7 years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.coindesk.com/down-26-bitcoin-sees-worst-sell-off-in-7-years-as-coronavirus-spurs-flight-to-safety |title=Down 26%: Bitcoin Sees Worst Sell-Off in 7 Years as Coronavirus Spurs Flight to Safety |date=12 March 2020 |website=CoinDesk  |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320130146/https://www.coindesk.com/down-26-bitcoin-sees-worst-sell-off-in-7-years-as-coronavirus-spurs-flight-to-safety |archive-date=20 March 2020 |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> Other [[Cryptocurrency|cryptocurrencies]] fell sharply as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/billybambrough/2020/03/12/crypto-carnage-wipes-out-2020-gains-for-bitcoin-ethereum-ripples-xrp-litecoin-and-bitcoin-cash/ |title=Crypto Carnage Wipes Out 2020 Gains For Bitcoin, Ethereum, Ripple's XRP, Litecoin, And Bitcoin Cash |last=Bambrough |first=Billy |website=[[Forbes]]  |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312175718/https://www.forbes.com/sites/billybambrough/2020/03/12/crypto-carnage-wipes-out-2020-gains-for-bitcoin-ethereum-ripples-xrp-litecoin-and-bitcoin-cash/ |archive-date=12 March 2020 |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Black Monday II (16 March) ===\nOver the preceding weekend, the Saudi Arabian Monetary Authority announced a $13&nbsp;billion credit-line package to small and medium-sized companies,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://gulfnews.com/business/coronavirus-saudi-central-bank-announces-50-billion-riyal-package-1.1584209042418 |title=Coronavirus: Saudi Central Bank announces 50 billion riyal package |date=14 March 2020 |work=[[Gulf News]] |access-date=15 March 2020 |publisher=[[Al Nisr Publishing]]}}</ref> while South African President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] announced a fiscal stimulus package.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Maeko |first=Thando |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2020-03-15-ramaphosa-pledges-covid-19-economic-stimulus-package/ |title=Ramaphosa pledges Covid-19 economic stimulus package |date=15 March 2020 |work=[[Mail & Guardian]] |access-date=17 March 2020 |publisher=M&G Media Ltd}}</ref> The Federal Reserve announced that it would cut the federal funds rate target to 0%\u20130.25%, lower reserve requirements to zero, and begin a $700&nbsp;billion quantitative easing program.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Liesman |first=Steve |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/15/federal-reserve-cuts-rates-to-zero-and-launches-massive-700-billion-quantitative-easing-program.html |title=Federal Reserve cuts rates to zero and launches massive $700&nbsp;billion quantitative easing program |date=15 March 2020 |access-date=15 March 2020 |publisher=[[CNBC]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-central-banks/fed-cuts-interest-rates-to-near-zero-coordinates-with-other-central-banks-to-combat-coronavirus-idUSKBN21219K |title=Fed cuts interest rates to near zero, coordinates with other central banks to combat coronavirus |date=15 March 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]] |access-date=15 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/files/monetary20200315a1.pdf |title=Federal Reserve issues FOMC statement |date=15 March 2020 |publisher=Federal Reserve Board |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDow futures tumbled more than 1,000 points and Standard & Poor's 500 futures dropped 5%, triggering a circuit breaker.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/03/15/dow-futures-plunge-800-points-after-fed-surprises-markets-and-cuts-rate-zero/5053777002/ |title=Stocks poised for plunge Monday as Dow futures drop 1,000 points despite Fed rate cut to zero |last=Menton |first=Jessica |website=USA Today  |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316000421/https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/03/15/dow-futures-plunge-800-points-after-fed-surprises-markets-and-cuts-rate-zero/5053777002/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> On Monday 16 March, Asia-Pacific and European stock markets closed down (with the [[S&P/ASX 200]] setting a one-day record fall of 9.7%, collapsing 30% from the peak that was reached on 20 February).<ref>{{Cite news |last=Huang |first=Eustance |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/asia-markets-fed-cut-to-zero-china-industrial-production-coronavirus.html |title=Australia stocks drop nearly 10% as Asia markets tumble; Fed cuts rates to zero |date=16 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316011317/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/asia-markets-fed-cut-to-zero-china-industrial-production-coronavirus.html |archive-date=16 March 2020 |publisher=[[CNBC]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Smith |first=Elliot |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/european-markets-spooked-as-regional-shutdown-widens.html |title=European stocks close down 5%, travel stocks tank 10% as EU proposes flight restrictions |date=16 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316082009/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/european-markets-spooked-as-regional-shutdown-widens.html |archive-date=16 March 2020 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |last2=Ellyatt |first2=Holly}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Hutchens |first=Gareth |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-16/coronavirus-fears-see-australian-market-slump-to-start-new-week/12058904 |title=ASX 200 posts biggest fall on record, Reserve Bank flags further measures amid coronavirus fears |date=16 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316131240/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-16/coronavirus-fears-see-australian-market-slump-to-start-new-week/12058904 |archive-date=16 March 2020 |publisher=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |last2=Chalmers |first2=Stephanie }}</ref> The Dow Jones Industrial Average, the NASDAQ Composite, and the S&P 500 all fell by 12\u201313%, with the Dow eclipsing the one-day drop record set on 12 March and the trading curb being activated at the beginning of trading for the third time (after 9 and 12 March).<ref name=\"DJIA0316\">{{Cite news |last=Imbert |first=Fred |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/15/traders-await-futures-open-after-fed-cuts-rates-launches-easing-program.html |title=Dow drops nearly 3,000 points, as coronavirus collapse continues; worst day since '87 |date=16 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316205041/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/15/traders-await-futures-open-after-fed-cuts-rates-launches-easing-program.html |archive-date=16 March 2020 |publisher=[[CNBC]] }}</ref> Oil prices fell by 10%,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stevens |first=Pippa |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/oil-drops-more-than-6percent-breaking-below-30.html |title=Oil drops nearly 10%, breaking below $29 as demand evaporates |date=16 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317071536/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/oil-drops-more-than-6percent-breaking-below-30.html |archive-date=17 March 2020 |publisher=[[CNBC]]}}</ref> while the yields on 10-year and 30-year U.S. Treasury securities fell to 0.76% and 1.38% respectively (while their [[yield curve]] remained [[Yield curve#Normal yield curve|normal]] for the third straight trading session).<ref>{{Cite news |last=Li |first=Yun |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/treasury-yields-fall-after-fed-cuts-rates-to-zero.html |title=10-year Treasury yield falls below 0.8% after Fed's emergency move to cut rates to zero |date=16 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316082207/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/treasury-yields-fall-after-fed-cuts-rates-to-zero.html |archive-date=16 March 2020 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |last2=Smith |first2=Elliot}}</ref>\n\nThe [[VIX|Cboe Volatility Index]] closed at 82.69 on 16 March, the highest ever closing for the index (though there were higher intraday peaks in 2008).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-16/stock-market-volatility-tops-financial-crisis-with-vix-at-record |title=Stock Market Volatility Tops Financial Crisis With VIX at Record |date=16 March 2020 |work=Bloomberg |access-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318143931/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-16/stock-market-volatility-tops-financial-crisis-with-vix-at-record |archive-date=18 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/wall-streets-fear-gauge-hits-highest-level-ever.html |title=Wall Street's fear gauge closes at highest level ever, surpassing even financial crisis peak |last=Li |first=Yun |date=16 March 2020 |publisher=CNBC |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317034842/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/wall-streets-fear-gauge-hits-highest-level-ever.html |archive-date=17 March 2020 |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> Around noon on 16 March, the [[Federal Reserve Bank of New York]] announced that it would conduct a $500&nbsp;billion [[Repurchase agreement|repurchase]] through the afternoon of that day.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cox |first=Jeff |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/fed-says-it-will-offer-an-additional-500-billion-in-overnight-repo-funding-markets.html |title=Fed says it will offer an additional $500&nbsp;billion in overnight repo funding markets |date=16 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316165654/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/fed-says-it-will-offer-an-additional-500-billion-in-overnight-repo-funding-markets.html |archive-date=16 March 2020 |publisher=[[CNBC]] }}</ref> Indonesian Finance Minister Sri Mulyani announced an additional Rp22&nbsp;trillion in tax-related fiscal stimulus.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Akhlas |first=Adrian Wail |url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/16/indonesia-deploys-second-stimulus-amid-market-rupiah-routs.html |title=Indonesia deploys second stimulus amid market, rupiah routs |date=16 March 2020 |work=[[The Jakarta Post]] |access-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317162401/https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/16/indonesia-deploys-second-stimulus-amid-market-rupiah-routs.html |archive-date=17 March 2020 |publisher=PT Niskala Media Tenggara}}</ref> The Central Bank of the Republic of Turkey lowered its reserve requirement from 8% to 6%.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/turkey-cenbank-remunar/turkish-central-bank-lowers-remuneration-rate-on-required-reserves-bankers-idUSI7N2B400E |title=Turkish central bank lowers remuneration rate on required reserves -bankers |date=16 March 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]] |access-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318150059/https://www.reuters.com/article/turkey-cenbank-remunar/turkish-central-bank-lowers-remuneration-rate-on-required-reserves-bankers-idUSI7N2B400E |archive-date=18 March 2020 }}</ref> The Bank of Japan announced that it would not cut its bank rate lower from \u22120.1% but that it would conduct more open market purchases of [[Exchange-traded fund]]s.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/03/16/business/economy-business/bank-of-japan-policy-meeting/#.XnAWHS-ZNp8 |title=BOJ ramps up risky asset buying as central banks fight coronavirus fallout |date=16 March 2020 |work=[[Japan Times]] |access-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317164142/https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/03/16/business/economy-business/bank-of-japan-policy-meeting/#.XnAWHS-ZNp8 |archive-date=17 March 2020 |publisher=News2u Holdings, Inc.}}</ref> After cutting its bank rate by 25 basis points on 7 February,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kollmeyer |first=Barbara |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/russian-ruble-falls-as-central-bank-cuts-key-rate-by-25-basis-points-to-6-2020-02-07 |title=Russian ruble falls as central bank cuts key rate by 25 basis points to 6% |date=7 February 2020 |access-date=5 March 2020 |website=[[MarketWatch]]}}</ref> the Central Bank of Russia announced that it would keep its bank rate at 6%,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ostroukh |first=Andrey |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-cenbank-rates/russia-seen-holding-key-rate-at-6-on-friday-amid-coronavirus-low-oil-idUSKBN21325V |title=Russia seen holding key rate at 6% on Friday amid coronavirus, low oil |date=16 March 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]] |access-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317110708/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-cenbank-rates/russia-seen-holding-key-rate-at-6-on-friday-amid-coronavirus-low-oil-idUSKBN21325V |archive-date=17 March 2020  |last2=Fabrichnaya |first2=Elena}}</ref> while the Bank of Korea announced that it would cut its overnight rate by 50 basis points to 0.75%.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/banking/bank-of-korea-slashes-rate-in-emergency-move-after-us-fed-cut |title=Bank of Korea slashes rate in emergency move after US Fed cut |date=16 March 2020 |work=[[The Straits Times]] |access-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317080740/https://www.straitstimes.com/business/banking/bank-of-korea-slashes-rate-in-emergency-move-after-us-fed-cut |archive-date=17 March 2020 |publisher=[[Singapore Press Holdings]]}}</ref> The [[Central Bank of Chile]] cut its benchmark rate,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sanyal |first=Shreyashi |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/emerging-markets-latam/emerging-markets-latam-fx-caught-in-virus-driven-rout-chile-central-bank-cuts-rates-idUSL1N2B94N9 |title=EMERGING MARKETS-Latam FX caught in virus-driven rout; Chile central bank cuts rates |date=16 March 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]] |access-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316193927/https://www.reuters.com/article/emerging-markets-latam/emerging-markets-latam-fx-caught-in-virus-driven-rout-chile-central-bank-cuts-rates-idUSL1N2B94N9 |archive-date=16 March 2020 }}</ref> while the [[Reserve Bank of New Zealand]] cut its [[official cash rate]] by 75 basis points to 0.25%.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Menon |first=Praveen |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-newzealand-economy-rbnz/new-zealand-central-bank-slashes-rates-at-emergency-meeting-as-coronavirus-worsens-idUSKBN2121FG |title=New Zealand central bank slashes rates at emergency meeting as coronavirus worsens |date=15 March 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]] |access-date=30 March 2020 }}</ref> The [[Czech National Bank]] announced that it would cut its bank rate by 50 basis points to 1.75%.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Komuves |first=Anita |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/easteurope-markets/update-2-cee-markets-assets-fall-even-as-central-banks-act-to-fight-virus-impact-idUSL8N2B9552 |title=UPDATE 2-CEE MARKETS-Assets fall even as central banks act to fight virus impact |date=16 March 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]] |access-date=31 March 2020  |last2=Hovet |first2=Jason}}</ref>\n\n== Impact by country ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== Africa ===\n[[Sub-Saharan Africa]] is poised to enter its first recession in 25 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldbank.org/en/news/press-release/2020/04/09/covid-19-coronavirus-drives-sub-saharan-africa-toward-first-recession-in-25-years|title=COVID-19 (Coronavirus) Drives Sub-Saharan Africa Toward First Recession in 25 Years|website=World Bank|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n==== Botswana ====\n[[Botswana]] has been affected by sharp falls in the diamond trade and tourism.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== Ethiopia ====\n[[Ethiopia]] is heavily dependent for export income on its national carrier, [[Ethiopian Airlines]], which has announced suspensions on 80 flight routes.<ref name=\":3\" /> Exports of flowers and other agricultural products have dropped sharply.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n=== Americas ===\n\n==== Argentina ====\n[[Argentina]] may face its 9th [[sovereign default]] in history due to the recession.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2020/04/22/covid-19-and-debt-argentinas-make-or-break-moment|title=Covid-19 and debt: Argentina\u2019s make-or-break moment|work=The Economist|access-date=2020-04-23|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\n==== Belize ====\nThe fall in travel is expected to drive Belize into a deep recession in 2020.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== Canada ====\nIn Canada, the unemployment figure was 1 million for the month of March.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52232674|title=Canada lost a record one million jobs in March|date=9 April 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Mexico ====\nMexico's outlook was already poor before the crisis, with a mild recession in 2019.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=Gladstone|first=Rick|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/22/world/middleeast/oil-price-collapse-coronavirus.html|title=Oil Collapse and Covid-19 Create Toxic Geopolitical Stew|date=2020-04-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The economic development plans of president [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]] were predicated on revenue from the state oil company [[Pemex]], but the oil price collapse has now raised doubts on those plans.<ref name=\":4\" /> Beyond oil, the country's economy also relies on tourism, trade with the [[United States]], as well as remittances, which all are also being affected.<ref name=\"economist1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2020/04/16/mexicos-bazooka-shy-president|title=Mexico\u2019s bazooka-shy president|work=The Economist|access-date=2020-04-23|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> All of this leading to what could be Mexico's worst recession in a century, and the worst in [[Latin America]] after [[Venezuela]].<ref name=\"economist1\"/>\n\n==== United States ====\n16&nbsp;million jobs were lost in the United States alone in the three weeks ending on 4 April.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Rushe|first1=Dominic|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/apr/09/us-unemployment-filings-coronavirus|title=US unemployment rises 6.6m in a week as coronavirus takes its toll|date=9 April 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=10 April 2020|last2=Sainato|first2=Michael|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> A new record of unemployment claims was made, with 3.3&nbsp;million claims made in the week ending on 21 March, with the previous record being 700,000 from 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/26/21195171/new-unemployment-claims-march-21|title=Chart: New unemployment claims soar to 3.3 million, shattering previous records|last=Yglesias|first=Matthew|date=26 March 2020|website=Vox|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> Restaurant patronage has fallen sharply across the country,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/16/21181556/coronavirus-chart-restaurant-business-local|title=Chart: How coronavirus is devastating the restaurant business|last=Molla|first=Rani|date=16 March 2020|website=Vox|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> and major airlines are reducing their operations on a large scale.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/airline-news/2020/03/18/coronavirus-travel-fallout-united-jetblue-allegiant-slash-flights/2863432001/|title=American Airlines cuts 55,000 flights, parks 450 planes amid coronavirus: 'Fight of our lives'|last=Gilbertson|first=Dawn|website=USA Today|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Big Three (automobile manufacturers)|Big Three car manufacturers]] have all halted production.<ref>{{cite news|author=Peter Valdes-Dapena and Vanessa Yurkevich|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/18/business/gm-ford-automakers-us-shut-down/index.html|title=GM, Ford and other automakers to halt production in the US|access-date=26 March 2020|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nThe US [[Inverted yield curve|yield curve inverted]] in 2019, usually indicative of a forthcoming recession.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/yield-curve-inversion-3-month-10-year-yield-curve-inverts-2019-5-1028187644|title=A closely followed recession indicator is flashing its most worrying sign in 12 years {{!}} Markets Insider|date=May 2019|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930224654/https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/yield-curve-inversion-3-month-10-year-yield-curve-inverts-2019-5-1028187644|archive-date=30 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-05-09/u-s-yield-curve-inverts-for-the-first-time-since-march|title=U.S. Yield Curve Inverts for the First Time Since March|date=May 2019|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.}}</ref> The [[St. Louis Fed Financial Stress Index]] increased sharply from below zero<!--21 Feb--> to 5.8<!--20 March--> during March 2020.<ref name=\"STLFSI2blog2\">{{cite web|url=https://fredblog.stlouisfed.org/2020/03/the-st-louis-feds-financial-stress-index-version-2-0/|title=The St. Louis Fed's Financial Stress Index, Version 2.0 {{!}} FRED Blog|date=26 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327224916/https://fredblog.stlouisfed.org/2020/03/the-st-louis-feds-financial-stress-index-version-2-0/|archive-date=27 March 2020|quote=The revised STLFSI, however, has increased sharply\u2014reminiscent of the worst of the financial market turmoil during the Great Recession in 2008\u20132009\u2014registering a value close to 5.8.}}</ref><ref name=\"STLFSI22\">{{cite web|url=https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/STLFSI2|title=St. Louis Fed Financial Stress Index (STLFSI2)|date=26 March 2020|website=FRED, Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327222839/https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/STLFSI2|archive-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Asia-Pacific ===\n\n==== Australia ====\n\nAustralia before the recession was suffering from an unusually severe and expensive [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season|bushfire season]] which damaged the economy and domestic trade routes.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Butler |first=Ben |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/jan/08/economic-impact-of-australias-bushfires-set-to-exceed-44bn-cost-of-black-saturday |title=Economic impact of Australia's bushfires set to exceed $4.4bn cost of Black Saturday |date=8 January 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=15 April 2020  |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Not only that, but Australia had experienced significant slowdown in their economic growth, with economists in late 2019 saying that Australia was 'teetering on the edge of a recession'.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-12-04/economy-to-continue-teetering-on-the-edge-of-recession/11761358 |title='80 per cent of the economy is going backwards', and that's likely to continue for some time |last=Taylor |first=David |date=4 December 2019 |website=ABC News  |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> As a result of this and the effects of the recession, Australia is expecting a deep recession with at least 10% of the able working population becoming unemployed according to the Australian treasury and a GDP retraction of at least \u22126.7% according to the IMF.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-14/imf-forecasts-big-coronavirus-growth-hit/12147818 |title=IMF says Australia's economy will shrink by 6.7 per cent this year |last=Hutchens |first=Gareth |date=14 April 2020 |website=ABC News  |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/en-au/news/australia/unemployment-rate-predicted-to-reach-10-per-cent-amid-coronavirus-pandemic-pushing-australia-into-recession/ar-BB12ywX2 |title=Unemployment rate predicted to reach 10 per cent amid coronavirus pandemic, pushing Australia into recession |publisher=MSN |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> In April 2020, a water consultant predicted a shortage of rice and other staples during the pandemic unless farmers' water allocations were changed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://9now.nine.com.au/60-minutes/rice-exports-coronavirus-water-expert-gareth-harvey/be067c3c-ebf7-4123-9a79-4ed6a5f3c75f |title=Top water expert predicts rice shortage |website=9now.nine.com.au  |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe unemployment level of 5.1% is projected to rise to a 25-year high of 10%, according to Treasury data released in April 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/australia-to-see-25-year-high-in-unemployment-report/1803909 |title=Australia to see 25-year high in unemployment: Report |website=aa.com.tr |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nestegg.com.au/invest-money/economy/treasury-expects-10-unemployment |title=Treasury expects 10% unemployment |last=Ormsby|first=Grace |date=14 April 2020 |website=nestegg.com.au  |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> The [[Social security in Australia#Jobseeker Allowance|Jobseeker Allowance]] unemployment benefit was doubled in April, but Prime Minister [[Scott Morrison]] said that this would likely be reduced when the pandemic ends.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/scott-morrison-says-jobseeker-payment-will-be-cut-after-pandemic |title=Scott Morrison says JobSeeker payment will be cut after pandemic |date=23 April 2020 |website=[[SBS World News]]}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2020, up to a million people have been laid off due to effects of the recession.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Henriques-Gomes |first=Luke |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/24/newly-unemployed-australians-queue-at-centrelink-offices-as-mygov-website-crashes-again |title=Newly unemployed Australians queue at Centrelink offices as MyGov website crashes again |date=24 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=26 March 2020 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Over 280,000 individuals applied for unemployment support at the peak day.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/surge-in-demand-280-000-ask-centrelink-for-help-in-one-day-20200325-p54dwn.html |title='Surge in demand': 280,000 ask Centrelink for help in one day |last=Bonyhady |first=Nick |date=25 March 2020 |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== China ====\nAs a result of the recession, [[Economy of China|China's economy]] contracted for the first time in almost 50 years.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bradsher|first=Keith|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/16/business/china-coronavirus-economy.html|title=China\u2019s Economy Shrinks, Ending a Nearly Half-Century of Growth|date=2020-04-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The national GDP for the first quarter of 2020 dropped 6.8% year-on-year, and the GDP for Hubei Province dropped 39.2% in the same period.<ref>{{cite news|author=Reuters |url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/21/world/asia/21reuters-china-economy-gdp-hubei.html |title=China's Hubei, Epicentre of Coronavirus Outbreak, Posts First-Quarter GDP Slump |via=New York Times |date= |accessdate=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== Iraq ====\nAs 90% of the government income comes from oil, it will be extremely heavily hit by the drop in prices.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==== Japan ====\nJapan's 2019 4th quarter GDP shrank 7.1% from the previous quarter<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Economy/Japan-s-Q4-GDP-downgraded-to-annualized-7.1-contraction|title=Japan's Q4 GDP downgraded to annualized 7.1% contraction|date=9 March 2020|work=Nikkei Asian Review|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> due to two main factors. One is the government's raise in [[consumption tax]] from 8 to 10% despite opposition from the citizens. The other is the devastating effects of [[Typhoon Hagibis]], also known as the Reiwa 1 East Japan Typhoon (\u4ee4\u548c\u5143\u5e74\u6771\u65e5\u672c\u53f0\u98a8, Reiwa Gannen Higashi-Nihon Taif\u016b), or Typhoon Number 19 (\u53f0\u98a819). The 38th depression, 9th typhoon and 3rd super typhoon of the [[2019 Pacific typhoon season]], it was the strongest typhoon in decades to strike mainland Japan, and one of the largest typhoons ever recorded at a peak diameter of 825 nautical miles (950&nbsp;mi; 1529&nbsp;km). It was also the costliest Pacific typhoon on record, surpassing [[Typhoon Mireille]]'s record by more than US$5 billion (when not adjusted for inflation).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tropical.atmos.colostate.edu/Realtime/index.php?loc=northwestpacific|title=Real-Time Northwest Pacific Ocean Statistics compared with climatology|date=|publisher=Tropical.atmos.colostate.edu|accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> In the resort town of Hokone, record rainfall of almost 1 meter (942.3 mm, 37.1 inches) fell in only 24 hours.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://watchers.news/2019/10/13/typhoon-hagibis-casualties-damage/|title=Widespread floods after extreme rainfall brought by Typhoon \"Hagibis\" - dozens dead or missing, Japan|date=13 October 2019|work=The Watchers|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> This adds to the effect of the Coronavirus on people's lives and the economy, the prime minister unveiling a 'massive\" stimulus amounting to 20% of GDP.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/04/06/business/shinzo-abe-japan-massive-coronavirus-stimulus/#.Xp0zH25uLIU|title=Abe unveils 'massive' coronavirus stimulus worth 20% of GDP|date=6 April 2020|work=The Japan Times|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Lebanon====\n{{further|2019\u201320 Lebanese protests}}\nSince August 2019, [[Lebanon]] had been experiencing a major economic crisis that was caused by an increase in the official exchange rate between the [[Lebanese pound]] and the [[United States dollar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bdl.gov.lb/statistics/table.php?name=t5282usd |title=Data Series |publisher=Bdl.gov.lb |date= |accessdate=2020-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/Business/Local/2020/Mar-11/502598-lebanons-gdp-declines-to-44-billion-from-55-billion.ashx |title=Lebanon\u2019s GDP declines to $44 billion from $55 billion &#124; Business , Local |publisher=The Daily Star |date=2020-03-11 |accessdate=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n==== Nepal ====\nAs millions of Nepalis work outside of the country, at least hundreds of thousands are expected to return due to layoffs abroad, in what has been labelled a \"crisis\" that may \"overwhelm the Nepali state\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/04/22/with-hundreds-of-thousands-of-migrants-predicted-to-return-home-nepal-needs-to-brace-for-a-crisis|title=With hundreds of thousands of migrants predicted to return home, Nepal needs to brace for a crisis|website=kathmandupost.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Europe ===\nThe European [[Purchasing Managers' Index]], a key indicator of economic activity, crashed to a record-low of 13.5 in April 2020.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/23/euro-zone-business-activity-crashes-to-shocking-lows-on-coronavirus.html|title=European business activity crashes to 'shocking' lows on coronavirus pandemic|last=Amaro|first=Silvia|date=2020-04-23|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> Normally, any figure below 50 is a sign of economic decline.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==== France ====\nFrance's [[Yellow vests movement|yellow vest movement]] caused significant economic damage to the French economy in 2019, alongside a global slowdown.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-46499996 |title=France protests 'an economic catastrophe' |date=9 December 2018 |work=BBC News |access-date=15 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-protests-idUSKCN1TS1RX |title=Worst of yellow vest economic impact in France yet to come: Senate |date=27 June 2019 |agency=Reuters |access-date=15 April 2020 }}</ref> France has being significantly hit hard by the pandemic, with two months of 'strict lockdown' imposed on the French society.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Willsher |first=Kim |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/13/macron-france-remain-strict-lockdown-for-another-month |title=France to remain in strict lockdown for another month |date=13 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=15 April 2020  |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 8 April, the [[Bank of France]] officially declared that the [[French economy]] was in recession, shrinking by 6 percent in the first quarter of 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200408-french-economy-drops-by-6-in-first-quarter-officially-in-recession |title=French economy enters recession with 6% drop in first quarter, its worst since 1945 |date=8 April 2020 |publisher=France 24  |access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Germany ====\nMinister of Finance of [[Hesse]], [[Thomas Sch\u00e4fer]], was found dead on 28 March 2020. Sch\u00e4fer left a suicide note, where he mentions the \"hopeless\" economic situation in the country as one of the reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tichyseinblick.de/daili-es-sentials/zum-tod-des-hessischen-finanzministers-thomas-schaefer/|title=Zum Tod des hessischen Finanzministers Thomas Sch\u00e4fer|date=29 March 2020|website=Tichys Einblick|language=de}}</ref>\n\n==== Italy ====\n[[Italy]]'s unemployment rate is expected to rise to 11.2%, with 51% fearing unemployment in March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/1109090/forecasted-unemployment-rate-in-italy/ |title=Italy: COVID-19 impact on unemployment rate 2020\u20132021 |website=Statista  |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/1105187/fear-of-losing-the-job-due-to-coronavirus-in-italy/ |title=Italy: fear of losing the job due to coronavirus 2020 |website=Statista  |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== United Kingdom ====\nThe [[Office for Budget Responsibility]] has suggested that unemployment could rise above the two million mark, returning to the highest level of unemployment since 1992 and an economic contraction of \u221235%. [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[Rishi Sunak]], announced unprecedented government spending measures of \u00a3350&nbsp;billion on 17 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/apr/14/uk-economy-could-shrink-by-35-with-2m-job-losses-warns-obr|title=UK economy could shrink by 35% with 2m job losses, warns OBR|date=16 April 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-britain-sunak-high/highlights-uks-sunak-goes-all-out-to-avert-economic-collapse-idUSKBN217352|title=Highlights: UK's Sunak goes all out to avert economic collapse|date=16 April 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n== Summary of national impacts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Effect on national economies by [[Economist Intelligence Unit]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.economist.com/economic-and-financial-indicators/2020/04/25/economic-data-commodities-and-markets|title=Economic data, commodities and markets|date=|work=The Economist|access-date=2020-04-22|url-status=live|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n!Country\n!Effect on annual GDP (%)\n!Unemployment (%)\n!Effect on main stock index during 2020 (%)\n|-\n|[[Austria]]\n| -6.0\n|4.4\n|\n